# static:: vs self::

When using `self::`, the class where the method is defined is used. With `static::`, the class that was called at runtime is used (late static binding).

```php
class ParentClass {
    public static function who() {
        echo __CLASS__;
    }

    public static function testSelf() {
        self::who();
    }

    public static function testStatic() {
        static::who();
    }
}

class ChildClass extends ParentClass {
    public static function who() {
        echo __CLASS__;
    }
}

ChildClass::testSelf();    // outputs ParentClass
ChildClass::testStatic();  // outputs ChildClass
```

# Common Magic Methods

PHP provides several magic methods (starting with `__`) that are called automatically in certain situations:

*   `__construct()`, `__destruct()`
*   `__get($prop)`, `__set($prop, $value)` – for accessing inaccessible properties.
*   `__call($name, $args)` – for invoking inaccessible methods.
*   `__toString()` – when object is treated as a string.
*   `__invoke($x)` – when object is called as a function.

Example:
```php
class User {
    private $data = [];

    public function __set($name, $value) {
        $this->data[$name] = $value;
    }

    public function __get($name) {
        return $this->data[$name] ?? null;
    }
}

$user = new User();
$user->name = 'Alice';
echo $user->name; // Alice
```

```php
<?php
class Stringable {
    private $value;

    public function __construct($value) {
        $this->value = $value;
    }

    public function __toString() {
        return (string) $this->value;
    }
}

$obj = new Stringable(123);
echo $obj; // 123, automatically calls __toString()
?>
```
